element_texts.text:
Dear Sherwood,

       I got your letter this

morning and decided after all to
ask you for the water colors. I 
got a bad impression that day I 
went to Baltimore to see about the
show. I decided that I would
go thru with it but it wasn't
worth while to go to a lot of
trouble. I think now it is
a better chance and if I am
doing it at all I had better
make the best effort I can.
The Charcoal Club altho it has 
rather gone to seed still has a 
certain prestige in Baltimore and
I think your Foreword will do
a good deal to draw people.

    That is fine about John

Lineweaver wanting a water color.
I couldn't send him any to
choose from right now for every-
thing I have is much is
going into the exhibition. Prehaps

He might be in Baltimore and see the show. Practically all the water colors there are priced around  $30
$25 + $30. One is $75+ ....
Perhaps I had better write a letter. I would like for him
to come here & see me. You know
a touch of queerness sometimes adds
a nice quality to a man.

   I went to Baltimore last

Saturday and saw Walther at his
home & studio. He is a rather pathetic
figure an honest and sincere man.
He has been sick. He has helped
his parents and he has two sons.
He taught twenty-five years at the
Maryland Institute, a terrible place.
Now when he is more more free to paint
illness begins to attack him.
He went wild after Matise and i
believe wasted many yearsin
abstract painting. He said he knows
no reason why painting should 
not be like music,free form

+ color. But good music proceeds from some strong feeling on the part of the composer. . Strong emotions I think arise in us from some outside stimulus. As a painter, in trying to put the emotion on  canvas a man trys to seize the essential things that produced that emotion. In cutting loose from the representation of the visual sensations we receive from this world I believe abstract painters are in a blind alley. It is all intellect & cannot affect us deeply. I saw some of Walther's abstracts but I liked his things after Matise better. One thing he showed me painted last year, these flower pots, was very nice. He told me Duncan Phillips had bought several of his painting's. That makes me think more of Duncan Phillips.. At least he must be willing to take a chance once in a while. I had always not quite understood the Book of the grotesque?

In Winesburg. I felt it deeply but at the same time it rather puzzled me. I was young. Saturday I saw so many grotesques in Baltimore.why is it that some people ? Grotesque young and others grow old and even shapeless and still they do not become grotesque? I felt after talking to Walther what a profound discouragement and weariness there is among thinking people now. Of course it is a phase. I wonder what new life   is gathering to burst forth. Perhaps  it is because we are straddling the division between two vast eras in human life. Well I am thankful I have painting. no matter how complicated life becomes, painting is something elemental like making love to woman. Charles
